problem:
Two masses $m_A = 2.0$ kg and $m_B = 5.0$ kg are on inclines and are connected together by a string as shown in the figure. The coefficient of kinetic friction between each mass and its incline is $\mu_k = 0.30$. If $m_A$ moves up, and $m_B$ moves down, determine their acceleration. \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{halfincline}
    \end{center}

(a) Suppose the coefficient of kinetic friction between $m_A$ and the plane in the figure is $\mu_k = 0.15$, and that $m_A = m_B = 2.7$ kg. As $m_B$ moves down, determine the magnitude of the acceleration of $m_A$ and $m_B$, given $\theta = 34^\circ$. (b) What smallest value of $\mu_k$ will keep the system from accelerating?
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{bed}
    \end{center}

solution:
\begin{anum}
        \item We define the downward motion as positive, so the net force is $$F=m_Bg-m_Ag\sin\theta-m_Ag\mu_k\cos\theta=8.37\, \unit N$$ so the net acceleration is $a=F/(m_A+m_B)=1.55\, \unit{m/s^2}.$
        \item We want the net force to equal 0 so it holds that $$\mu_k=\frac{m_Bg-m_Ag\sin\theta}{m_Ag\cos\theta}=0.53$$
    \end{anum}

Drawing a proper diagram is key here, especially because the setup is a bit confusing. Here is a top-down diagram:
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[width=6cm]{les_mis.png}
    \end{center}
    Now, looking at this, we see that the horizontal components of friction exactly cancel out the normal forces. Using this, we can write that at saturation,
    $$0 = F_y = 2F_{f_y} - mg = 2\sqrt{(\mu N)^2 - N^2} - mg.$$
    We see that for this to be possible we must have $\mu > 1$ and then pushing hard enough (large enough $N$) is sufficient. For computing the minimum force on each wall, we first have
    $$N = \frac{mg}{2} \frac{1}{\sqrt{\mu^2 - 1}},$$ but for the total force we must sum the friction force and normal force which is bigger by $\sqrt{1 + \mu^2}$, so $$F_{min} = \frac{mg}{2} \sqrt{\frac{\mu^2 + 1}{\mu^2 - 1}}.$$
